<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I257d4190630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>B.</label.designator><headtext>Competency</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05bf682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:8.</label.designator><headtext>Mental capacity</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The traditional test is whether the individual has intelligence enough to make it worthwhile to hear him and whether he feels a duty to tell the truth.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I765d782074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] A witness who has been adjudged insane and is in a state sanitarium is not necessarily incompetent as a witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I765d782174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] However, on examination of the individual, the court may find that he lacks the capacity to testify.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I765d9f3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In a case of first impression, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1993058188" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I91b2317274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Dorsey v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I765d9f3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals upheld the trial court&apos;s admission of testimony from a witness in a dissociative state after receiving expert testimony that that the witness would not lie. <eos/><bos/>The witness, the victim of sexual abuse, had several distinctive personalities. <eos/><bos/>When exposed to upsetting situations, the witness retreated to the personality of a nine-year-old, and it was in this state that the victim gave testimony against the defendant.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I765d782074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1991118279" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I91b05cb274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Cook v. State, 199 Ga. App. 523, 405 S.E.2d 341 (1991)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I765d782174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1931106138" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I91b0d1e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Conoway v. State, 171 Ga. 782, 156 S.E. 664 (1931)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1939105683" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I91b0d1e574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bonner v. State, 59 Ga. App. 737, 1 S.E.2d 768 (1939)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>It does not matter if the insanity adjudication was in another state.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1965126864" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I91b1471274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Saxe v. State, 112 Ga. App. 804, 146 S.E.2d 376 (1965)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I765d9f3074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1924105319" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I91b1953274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ray v. State, 32 Ga. App. 513, 124 S.E. 57 (1924)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I765d9f3174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018081" w-serial-number="1993058188" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I91b2588274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Dorsey v. State, 206 Ga. App. 709, 426 S.E.2d 224 (1992)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
